segments.text: Now, on this College Hills area, were there a lot of trees on this area, or were most of these trees planted?
Was this mostly cotton fields?
This was primarily a cotton field area.
When I first moved into this home in about 39, you could still see the old drills throughout the area.
Incidentally, the city hall that you see down here, too,

done during my tenure as mayor we used to be located over in the old city hall that's at the north gate over there right and prior to that well when we first started out as a city we were in the building a two-story building over on south side that constituted our office part-time secretary and city manager and the city council
It was very small indeed, and gradually we went over to, we finally went to the north side, Northgate area, and then proceeded to, with the new city hall in the location where it is now.
And it was about that time, or at that time, that we also instituted a fire department
with some of our own men, and you were acquainted, of course, with the fire station here.
I was curious about that a while ago.
You said something about the A&M providing the fire protection for our college station at that time.
Now, could you give me an example or something, or do you ever remember when there was a fire, and how did that actually work, anyway?
Well, when there's a fire, Jerry, well, we usually call the fire number over at the power plant,
And they had the fire truck readiness at all times.
So it served as our... Now, we did pay a nominal amount to the university for the service at the time.
But I know that it cost them quite a bit.
And, of course, even those that served in the fire department were volunteer firemen.
Most of them worked in the power plant or in an area that...
In case of the fire, well, the truck went by, and they jumped on the truck, and off they went to help us out.
I see.
Yeah.

But I think it's interesting to point out, too, that some of my opposition, when I was trying to get the bond issue passed for the city hall and the fire station, said that we did not need a fire station.
He did not reckon this was a council meeting.
And he didn't want a fire station.
He said that it would be better if a home were to burn to the ground and get full restitution rather than have a fire department.
Now, this is some of the philosophy
that I was bucking and trying to make for a progressive community.
I was going to say, it doesn't seem to be too progressive for a councilman.

No, but this was the view I... As a matter of fact, when I went in and first had all this trouble on the city council and they were voting down everything that I was trying to do for the community, I got with the news people, the radio station and newspapers.
Yeah, the TV was then...
Yeah, the TV station was then here, and explained to them my dilemma, and I sought their cooperation.
And Mike Mistovich pledged that he would boost my presentation on the TV station.
That has boosted in terms of letting the public know that I was to appear several weeks before I appeared on TV.
And that was, I had the one-hour program right after Kosygin, who was in the United States, and it had a good listening audience.
And I went prepared with charts and maps.
and spoke to the public for one hour.
It was public service time.
I had a good listening audience.
That's prime time.
It sounded like that.
That's right.
And right after, Kosygin was featured.
And I invited the public out to the next council meeting.
And at the next council meeting, I brought up things that the public were interested in, but the majority against me would not endorse.
Well, following that meeting, that was all that was needed on the part of the public to get riled up.
And at the next council election, well, the people themselves saw that they went out with a landslide against them.
And it was only then that we were able to get in gear and do many of the things that needed to be done in the community.
As I said, you know, there were so many things that we lacked, and the university started to grow, and we needed to keep up with that growth.

We needed to encourage the building of homes, and we needed to institute ordinances that were necessary, like fire code, building code, ordinances that had to do with zoning, and things of this nature.
And for years, we had, I mean, we were just all the time trying to step out and be a little forward in all these areas.
Well, the zoning, what was the most of the zoning?
Was it mostly residential type zoning at that time when you first?
Well, residential primarily.
And of course, then eventually we got into zoning for business and the like.
But when did this, I know this shopping center over here now is probably the, it's been here for as long as I know it was one of the first ones that I can remember when I was going to school here.
Well, that was four years ago, big deal.
But this shopping center over here, when did that first go in?
Was it Gibson's?
Oh, well, that's, yeah.
Oh, gee, you know, I get rusty on dates.
In the 60s, was it?
Yeah, that must have been the late,
Yeah, that was about the middle 60s when that area was developed because there was nothing in there.
I mean, that was all open land as is the area across the street there, the highway.
That was all.
You remember who that land was owned by?
People over there before it was sold?
There were several ownerships.
I don't recall just who they were.
I see.
But...
That was practically all farmland from there south.
There was nothing in there.
Now, speaking of park area, just a moment, Jerry.
If I might, we had the Lincoln School.
It was a Negro school where the Lincoln Center now is.
And that area burned.
And at that period in our school history,
Then the Negro population was moved into the white school, and we have been integrated ever since.
Well, now that left that facility down there, that was school property and unoccupied.
And the city council made a deal with the school system whereby we would use that as a recreational area.
And I recall I got a lot of criticism again on this by moving out in this direction, but I think time has proved that it has served a good need in that community.
Now, we had a lot of problems to start with, very discouraging, because at night people would knock out the glass and break the doors and the furniture.
And I'll tell you, I became discouraged lots of times.
But faith prevailed, and fortunately today, it's taken care of, and I'm glad that it is serving the need in that particular community.

Now, the swimming pool, of course, at one time, we were directly, you might say, well, all my children and others of faculty and staff, the recreational activities were actually provided by Texas A&M.
And with the increasing use by the students, it became obvious that gradually we would have to get off campus, just like our school.
The university actually nurtured our city.
I see.
And like in the school, while we saw and we could foresee that we needed a swimming pool, we needed the development of our parks and things of this nature.
So, of course, this was another forward step that we had to make.
with the limited finances that we had available to us.
The school for College Station children was on the campus, and then when it moved off, it moved off to where it still is now.
The chicken coops.
Right.
Where they call them the chicken coops.
I see.

Well, as I said, the university actually nurtured the city and gradually it became necessary for us in terms of water, the school, recreation, housing, things of this nature to take over and gradually go ahead.
I'm happy to say that we have done it on a very reasonable
As a city, we do not have a large indebtedness.
It's not one that we can't carry with the bonds that we have.
We've been pretty much a pay-as-you-go.
We've tried to, or at least I did when I was on the council, work with the leaders of the student body.
Matter of fact, the lights that were put on the west side of the campus to prevent where the students parked their cars here in late years.
Working with the university, we chipped in on the cost for the mercury vapor lights that's on the west side of the campus.
And this was even brought out in court against me when they had me down here in county court.
They criticized me for working with the university and the students.
And my position then was, as it is now, that the student body itself
helped pay for this through the sales tax and other things that they purchased.
And we rightfully need to compensate them for what they did.

I think the student body as a whole that got larger, I guess, had a lot more of a buying power in the stores and merchandise in this area, and it's something that needed to be not really compensated for, but needed to be understood and
respect it, I guess, because they... Oh, yes, definitely so.
You can judge this by the business activities during the holiday period when the students are not here.
Right.
And this I respect very much, and I've always said that, of course, I wear a college station on my heart in terms of the pride in my city and the university.

Of course, being a university employee, or having been one, and very loyal to my city, and having been brought up when people were against us, you might say, imposed on me a little more loyalty, perhaps, than some new newcomer coming in today.
You might say, well, you're an old-timer.
Yes, I'm an old-timer, but I remember

you know the growing city and what it meant to us and how hard we strive to even though when we put in our little consolidated school over here we had a very small enrollment and with what taxes we had trying to expand that system we almost every month or so we had a program of some kind to try to raise money to put in sidewalks
provide this or provide that.
We just, we came up the hard way.
Right.
And this is part of that loyalty that I referred to.
Right.
We, you got a little more there, Jim?
Yeah, you go ahead.
I'm just looking over, you know, the little sheet that I have here, and in terms of

Showing leadership, I always took this position, joining with the council, the council joining with me, that we were planning to make College Station a showpiece for any city, I mean, with the progress.
And for a while, you know, I'm thinking here of the public health issue of
mosquitoes and diseases that it carries.
And we were one of the first cities in this part of the country to institute the traps that would catch mosquitoes.
Well, now when was this work started in this area?
Oh, I would say, Jerry, that was around 1967.
And the purpose there, of course, was to
prevent disease.
And these mosquitoes were then shipped down to Houston and looked at.
But for Brazos County, this was the first that we instituted.
And now another thing that I pushed very hard was this emergency telephone number, 99, 911, that very few people are aware of today, and I regret that they are not acquainted with it.
Because in times of emergency, if the number 911 was drilled into a person's mind, you could dial this number in the dark.
It is a universal number that is used in many parts of the United States and in foreign countries, even Canada.
And I tried to, well, I did bring this innovation into this area.
And at the time I was working on it, I asked the city of Bryan if they were interested in coming in with me, and they were not.
The county was not interested.
So single-handedly, we pushed this for College Station.
And this is another first.
We were one of the few cities in the state of Texas to have this emergency number.
Now, unfortunately, I did not live, I mean, my service as mayor was such
that the system was installed shortly after I left.
And unfortunately, the people were made unaware of the importance of this number.
Now, this 911 is dialed into our police station, and they have a record down there of any message through 911 is emergency.
And they have a list of doctors and anybody else that you might need
in terms of an emergency.
Now, a recent event just happened here in College Station where a man had a heart attack.
The wife went to the telephone.
She didn't know the doctor's number.
She didn't think about even trying to dial zero.
She was frustrated while her husband had a heart attack out in the lot.
Here is where I say that if this 911 was indelibly impressed on everybody's mind in terms of a heart attack, if you need oxygen, if you need a doctor in an emergency, things of this nature.
There's a prowler outside your window.
Your wife could discreetly go to the phone in the dark and number 911 and get the prowler in the act.
Unfortunately, this has not been publicized enough
really warrant its use today.
But it's very, very unfortunate.
Well, how about in the area of public health and care?
What has, have there been any ideas considered for a hospital, a college station hospital?
Are they used to use the Brazos?
Is there a hospital in Bryan?
We worked on this, Jerry, before I went out as mayor.
We had hopes, and I still have hopes today, that someday we will get a smaller hospital out in this area.
I know I was born in the hospital over here, St. Joseph's Hospital down in Bryan.
Oh, you were?
When my father was going to school here.
I just wondered about that.
Yeah.
Well, then the new hospital, St. Joseph's Hospital, we worked hard to get that.
That is a city council there, as a regional hospital.
And then subsequently, the old Bryan Hospital moved from their location downtown up to where nearby St. Joseph's.
But that is now run by a number of doctors.
And we had hopes of getting that particular chain interested in coming out to college days.
But in a lot of things you do, Jerry, there are politics at a higher level.
And I'm not denying this.
And this has seriously affected our city in times in the past.
But the city is growing.
And I have reason to hope that in the near future, in the next few years, we will see a hospital of some type in this particular area.
I dare say, and I said this while as mayor, that the time will come when the city of College Station will be larger than the city of Bryan.
Each year, the percentage of increase is showing this in terms of College Station over Bryan.
And we will be the dominant city of the two cities.
We have the area to the south for this particular growth.
And anyone riding around the city today, it's so obvious the potential in this particular area in contrast to brine.
Now limitations are set on both cities in terms of the flood plain to the east, the railroad track, and other university holdings to the west.
But we can grow south.
If and when the Milliken Dam ever comes in, why this will really make for an explosive situation, I believe, in our area in terms of population growth.
And you know
perhaps as well as I, that many people are coming to this area to retire.
And we have, in the Brazos County area now, six retirees groups.
And it's surprising to see the number of them.
Of course, a lot of them are faculty and staff from A&M.
But a lot of retired officers are coming here to live.
because of the opportunities that Texas A&M presents to anybody.
The opportunities are here for anything, so they come here.
Well, when the city first incorporated itself, how large has it grown in size?
Not in population size, mainly, but in, say,
footage or acreage size.
Can you, you know how much?
Is it double, say?
Oh, it's more than double.
In terms of acreage, I'm a little rusty on the figures now, but I would say that it has increased 10 times over what it was originally back in
Well, even as late as the 1950s, it's increased that much.
Well, you said there were six miles of difference between the Bryan and the College Station sea limits back in around 1939.
Is that right?
Yes.
Well, which way...
Has Brian taken over most of that six miles?
Well, yeah.
Well, see, when Brian extended their six miles, that gave them living room.
And thus the development on Highway 6, as you see it today, primarily.
Then the extension out towards 29th Street.
Not that way.
Our growth principally had to be to the south.
To the south.
Yes.
Because we were limited in terms of the railroad track and university holdings to the west.
Right.
And then we have the airport out there, and this has a limiting factor on development there.
Any structure over, you know, one story high because of the flight pattern.

And then with the future development of that airport, and I'm sure this is coming in not too many years, perhaps ten years, you will see a large expansion at Easterwood to take care of all the regional traffic that is being generated even now.
But our growth primarily is in the south and, of course, some to the east towards the floodplain.
Well, now, on that floodplain limitation, that's for the Navasota River, is that right?
Yeah, that's right.
Now, of course, we, in terms of ordinances,
We put in the sewage disposal plant down there just before I got on the council.
Before that, here's another instance where we're tied into the university, and eventually we went to our own sewage disposal plant.
In the case of meat, we had a problem, as any cities do that do not have a meat ordinance,
all kind of meat is dumped into an area where there is no ordinance prohibiting it.
And we had to do that.
You said that one time you used a water supply for the city.
You had to come from the university and from Bryan.
Now, do you still, I guess now, do you have your own wells now or not?
We do not have our own water supply.
At the present time, we buy both water and electricity from the city of Bryan.
And, of course, this helps Bryan in the sense that they generate
Well, I guess about one third of the revenues that the city of Bryan generates comes from College Station.
And this has enabled them to get into the construction program, like that lake and so on that they have there, that new cooling lake, has enabled them to expand their production for our use as well.

Now, say the growth back in the 1940s or so of College Station, was the influx of people into this area, was it mostly due to, I guess it was mostly due to the university being new staff and as the university grew, more people came into it.
Were there any other outside businesses or
manufacturing organizations that the city tried to promote in this area, College Station, or did they not?
Well, we did, Jerry.
Over the years, what we were trying to get into College Station, and I would still recommend we do, are industries that are university-oriented.
The university has facilities out here like the data processing center and all the expertise in all these areas.
that could be made available for quality.

I know we worked pretty hard when I was in there to get the Banana Institute here at A&M to set up their primary research facilities in this particular university community so that they would have the benefit of expertise in these various areas, soil and water and everything else.
for some reason they did not see fit to come here.
But some of the universities in the community came for this particular reason.
And this is a type of encouragement I have very much discouraged, like chicken pluckers and things of this nature, because not only is it a low scale outfit where they come into a city,
But then it creates a problem like for a sewage disposal plant.
When you get feathers and things like this in a sewage disposal system, it wrecks it pretty bad.
So things like this I had never encouraged personally.
Now I did, as mayor, I might point this out.
give every homeowner every year an annual report on the stewardship of our city.
When I went in as mayor, I felt this was an obligation on my part to let the people know about our income and our outgo and what we did, what the city employees were doing, things of this nature.
And right after I left, the annual report ceased.
We have never received a report from our city government.
I deem this very unfortunate.

Now, if the city has gotten so big that they feel that they cannot do this in terms of an annual report, I do feel that they owe it to the public through the media of the newspaper or the bat, you know, annual report to the citizens on their stewardship.
Now, the cities of San Angelo, San Antone, a lot of these cities do this.
And I see no reason why we shouldn't consider or continue to do this.
But since I left, there's been no annual report to the citizens on the stewardship of our city.
I throw this out because I was really sold on this matter of communicating with the citizens.
And also in recognizing the bad blood that had been created earlier between the City of Bryan and College Station and the like, I did institute meetings where we met maybe every three or four months.
Had a little dinner meeting where we could discuss what the City of College Station was doing, and we had hoped that Bryan would do the same thing.
so as to prevent any future misunderstandings or problems that might arise that each of us, you know, we're not familiar with.
And as I mentioned earlier, you know, there was some bad blood originally between the two cities.
I guess we're almost about out of tape here.
I just wanted to...

say thank you and appreciated it and I guess that's about all really I just thanks for the time well Jerry it's been my pleasure I could go on for hours beginning in you know each of the areas I mean public transportation you name it public health and I'm just full of it I mean because I have been involved even this sheet that I have here
This is one that I, for example, to feel out the public in terms of every area of growth, expansion, and area of activity within the city of College Station.
I sent this out, this is what, about 40 pages, and had many citizens review what I consider to be a plan of action.
And they returned it with their critique, and this formed the basis of my...
tenure in office and trying to do what was needed in the community.
So I thank you, Jerry.
